<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <title>Geek Reader - Awesome reader for geeks</title>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <meta name="description" content="Read technical blogs, Hacker News. Customize your reading experience and this is open source!">
  <meta name="keywords" content="Geek Reader">
  <%= stylesheet_link_tag    "application", media: "all", "data-turbolinks-track" => false %>
  <%= javascript_include_tag "application"%>
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, user-scale=no">
  <%= csrf_meta_tags %>
</head>
<body>

<div class="container">
      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-xs-8">
          <%= link_to(content_tag("h1", "Geek Reader"), :root, class: "geek_reader") %>
        </div>
        <div class="col-xs-4">
          <span class="login pull-right"><%=link_to("Login Now", :login, :class => "btn btn-default") %></span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <summary>An awesome reader for Geeks like you!</summary>
      <p>
        <div class="screen_shot">
          <%= image_tag("gr_screenshot.gif") %>
        </div>
      </p>
      <ul class="row features">
        <li class="col-md-4 list-unstyled">
          <h3>Code Highlighting</h3>
          <p>
            It uses Hightlight.js for highlighting code snippet. Every article will have a consistent look of their code snippets.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li class="col-md-4 list-unstyled">
          <h3>Custom Styles</h3>
          <p>
            You can customize the stylesheets of any feed, so you can hide those ignoring 1px images and more.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li class="col-md-4 list-unstyled">
          <h3>Secondary Fetching</h3>
          <p>
            Feed sources like HackerNews can be set to fetch content from feed url. So you will not need to click the link to see it's content.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-8">
          <p>Besides those, you still get all the goodies of a normal reader app.</p>

          <ul class="other_features">
            <li>Periodic updates</li>
            <li>Email notifications</li>
            <li>Mobile support</li>
          </ul>
          <p>Last but not least, it's <a href="https://github.com/coderek/geek-reader">open source!</a> You can modify it to suit your own needs.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4">
          <strong>Share</strong>
          <%= social_share_button_tag("Geek Reader", {:url => "http://geek-reader.com", :image=>image_path("gr_screenshot.gif")}) %>
        </div>
      </div>

  <footer class="footer">&copy; Derek Zeng 2014</footer>
</div>
<%= render "common/tracking" %>
</body>
</html>
